INSERT INTO courses (id, slug, title, description, level, image_url) VALUES ('2c20e72b-36b9-581d-a7de-b94661a4f498', 'rust-concurrency', '{"EN": "Async Rust & Concurrency Masterclass", "ES": "Masterclass: Rust As\u00edncrono y Concurrencia"}', '{"EN": "The ultimate guide to concurrent systems. From OS threads and Atomics to the deep internals of the Future trait, Tokio runtime architecture, and advanced synchronization patterns.", "ES": "La gu\u00eda definitiva de sistemas concurrentes. Desde hilos del SO y At\u00f3micos hasta los internos del trait Future, arquitectura de Tokio y patrones avanzados."}', 'Intermediate', 'https://placehold.co/800x500/0F766E/FFFFFF/png?text=Async+Masterclass&font=roboto');
INSERT INTO modules (id, course_id, title, "order") VALUES ('fde33563-5500-5bdf-9873-d4b187725f96', '2c20e72b-36b9-581d-a7de-b94661a4f498', '{"EN": "1. OS Threads & Primitives", "ES": "1. Hilos del SO y Primitivas"}', 1);
INSERT INTO chapters (id, module_id, title, content, is_quiz, quiz_data, "order") VALUES ('90adf501-0f66-5969-887b-904ef0561d5e', 'fde33563-5500-5bdf-9873-d4b187725f96', '{"EN": "The Evolution: From OS Threads to Async", "ES": "La Evoluci\u00f3n: De Hilos SO a Async"}', '{"EN": "# The Landscape of Concurrency\n\nTo master Async Rust, we must first understand the foundation upon which it stands: **Operating System Threads** and why they aren''t enough for every use case.\n\n## 1. The 1:1 Threading Model\nRust''s standard library (`std::thread`) utilizes a **1:1 Threading Model**. This means that every time you call `thread::spawn`, Rust makes a system call to the Kernel to create a genuine OS thread (e.g., `pthread` on Linux, `CreateThread` on Windows).\n\n### Preemptive Multitasking\nThe OS Kernel is the manager. It allows a thread to run for a specific \"time slice\" (quantum). When that time is up, or when the thread blocks (waits for I/O), the Kernel performs a **Context Switch**:\n1.  Halt the CPU execution of the current thread.\n2.  Save all CPU registers, program counter, and stack pointer to RAM (Thread Control Block).\n3.  Flush CPU caches (TLB), which is computationally expensive.\n4.  Load the state of the next thread.\n5.  Resume execution.\n\nThis process ensures fairness but incurs latency (microseconds range).\n\n## 2. The Cost of \"Heavy\" Threads\nWhile powerful for CPU-bound tasks, OS threads come with overhead that limits scalability for I/O:\n*   **Memory Overhead**: Each OS thread creates a Stack. On Linux, the default stack size is **2MB** (reserved virtual memory). Spawning 10,000 threads implies requesting ~20GB of addressable memory, causing OOM (Out of Memory) issues on smaller machines.\n*   **Scheduling Overhead**: Switching between thousands of threads burns CPU cycles just managing the switches rather than executing your code. The kernel scheduler degrades to O(n) or O(log n) performance with too many active threads.\n\n## 3. The \"C10K Problem\"\nIn the early 2000s, web servers struggled to handle 10,000 concurrent connections. If you assign **One Thread per Connection**, you run out of RAM before you run out of CPU power. \n\nIf your server receives a request and needs to query a Database, the thread calls `socket.read()`. This **Blocks** the thread. The OS puts it to sleep. That expensive 2MB stack sits in RAM doing nothing, waiting for a network packet.\n\n## 4. The Solution: Async & Green Threads\nThis is why methods like `async/.await` exist. They move the scheduling from the **OS Kernel** to **User Space** (your application).\n\n*   **Cooperative Multitasking**: Instead of the OS pausing your thread forcibly, your code *voluntarily* yields control (`.await`) when it knows it has to wait.\n*   **State Machines**: Rust compiles async functions into State Machines. These are tiny structs (often < 500 bytes) that contain only the variables needed across waiting points.\n*   **M:N Model**: An Async Runtime (like Tokio) runs tens of thousands of these tiny tasks (M) on top of a very small number of OS threads (N), usually equal to the number of CPU cores.\n\n## Summary\n*   **Use std::thread**: For heavy CPU calculations (Parallelism) where you need to use all cores constantly (e.g., Image processing, Encryption).\n*   **Use Async**: For I/O bound tasks (Web Servers, DB Drivers) where tasks spend most of their time waiting for external events.", "ES": "# El Panorama de la Concurrencia\n\nPara dominar Async Rust, primero debemos entender los cimientos: **Los Hilos del Sistema Operativo** y por qu\u00e9 no son suficientes para todos los casos.\n\n## 1. El Modelo de Hilos 1:1\nLa librer\u00eda est\u00e1ndar de Rust (`std::thread`) usa un **Modelo 1:1**. Cada vez que llamas a `thread::spawn`, Rust hace una llamada al Kernel para crear un hilo real del SO (ej. `pthread` en Linux).\n\n### Multitarea Apropiativa (Preemptive)\nEl Kernel es el jefe. Permite que un hilo corra por un \"intervalo de tiempo\" (quantum). Cuando acaba, o el hilo se bloquea (espera I/O), el Kernel hace un **Cambio de Contexto**:\n1.  Detiene la CPU.\n2.  Guarda registros, contador de programa y puntero de stack en RAM (TCB).\n3.  Limpia cach\u00e9s de CPU (TLB), lo cual es costoso.\n4.  Carga el estado del siguiente hilo.\n5.  Reanuda.\n\nEste proceso asegura equidad pero incurre en latencia (rango de microsegundos).\n\n## 2. El Costo de los Hilos \"Pesados\"\n*   **Sobrecarga de Memoria**: Cada hilo crea un Stack. En Linux, el tama\u00f1o por defecto es **2MB**. Lanzar 10,000 hilos implica pedir ~20GB de memoria virtual.\n*   **Sobrecarga de Planificaci\u00f3n**: Cambiar entre miles de hilos quema ciclos de CPU solo gestionando los cambios. El planificador del kernel degrada su rendimiento con demasiados hilos activos.\n\n## 3. El Problema \"C10K\"\nSi asignas **Un Hilo por Conexi\u00f3n**, te quedas sin RAM antes que sin CPU. Si tu servidor espera una Base de Datos, el hilo se **Bloquea**. Ese stack costoso de 2MB se queda en RAM sin hacer nada.\n\n## 4. La Soluci\u00f3n: Async y Green Threads\nAqu\u00ed entra `async/.await`. Mueven la planificaci\u00f3n del **Kernel** al **Espacio de Usuario**.\n\n*   **Multitarea Cooperativa**: En lugar de que el SO pause tu hilo a la fuerza, tu c\u00f3digo cede el control *voluntariamente* (`.await`) cuando sabe que debe esperar.\n*   **M\u00e1quinas de Estado**: Rust compila funciones async en M\u00e1quinas de Estado. Son structs diminutos (a menudo < 500 bytes).\n*   **Modelo M:N**: Un Runtime (como Tokio) corre miles de estas tareas (M) sobre un n\u00famero peque\u00f1o de hilos del SO (N)."}', false, NULL, NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!(\"I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.\");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!(\"Main thread finishes.\");\n}', NULL, E'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, E'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, E'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!(\"I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.\");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!(\"Main thread finishes.\");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!(\"I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.\");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!(\"Main thread finishes.\");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!("I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!("Main thread finishes.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\nuse std::time::Duration;\n\nfn main() {\n    // This is an OS Thread. It is expensive to create.\n    let handle = thread::spawn(|| {\n        println!(\"I am a distinct execution context managed by the Kernel.\");\n        \n        // This ''sleep'' blocks the entire OS thread.\n        thread::sleep(Duration::from_secs(1));\n    });\n\n    handle.join().unwrap();\n    println!(\"Main thread finishes.\");\n}', 1);
INSERT INTO chapters (id, module_id, title, content, is_quiz, quiz_data, "order") VALUES ('700d605c-3f78-5c73-901f-d48c822374e6', 'fde33563-5500-5bdf-9873-d4b187725f96', '{"EN": "Scoped Threads Internals", "ES": "Internos de Hilos Scoped"}', '{"EN": "# The ''static Lifetime Problem\nIn standard threads (`thread::spawn`), the closure passed must have a `''static` lifetime. Why?\nBecause `thread::spawn` returns a `JoinHandle`. You are *not required* to call `.join()`. The main thread could finish, pop its stack frame, and destroy its local variables while the spawned thread is still running. If the spawned thread held a reference to those locals, it would access invalid memory (Use-After-Free).\n\nTherefore, standard threads must **own** all their data (via `move`) or use reference counting (`Arc`).\n\n# Scoped Threads (Rust 1.63+)\n`thread::scope` introduces a new paradigm. It guarantees that **all threads spawned within the scope will join before the scope ends**.\n\n## How it works\nThe scope function provides a `Scope` object. This object allows spawning threads that do not need to be `''static`. They only need to live as long as the scope.\nAt the end of the `scope` block, the compiler automatically inserts join points for all spawned threads. If a thread panics, the panic is propagated.\n\n## Benefits\n*   **Zero-Overhead Sharing**: You can lend references (`&mut T`) to threads without `Arc` or `Mutex` if you can prove disjoint access.\n*   **Fork-Join Parallelism**: Ideal for dividing an array into chunks and processing them in parallel without heap allocation for `Arc`.", "ES": "# El Problema del Lifetime ''static\nEn hilos est\u00e1ndar, el closure debe ser `''static`. \u00bfPor qu\u00e9?\nPorque `thread::spawn` no te obliga a llamar `.join()`. El hilo principal podr\u00eda terminar, destruir su stack y sus variables locales mientras el hilo hijo sigue corriendo. Si el hijo tuviera una referencia a esas locales, acceder\u00eda a memoria inv\u00e1lida.\n\nPor tanto, los hilos est\u00e1ndar deben **poseer** sus datos (`move`) o usar `Arc`.\n\n# Hilos Scoped (Rust 1.63+)\n`thread::scope` garantiza que **todos los hilos lanzados dentro del \u00e1mbito terminar\u00e1n antes de que el \u00e1mbito cierre**.\n\n## C\u00f3mo funciona\nAl final del bloque `scope`, el compilador inserta autom\u00e1ticamente puntos de uni\u00f3n (join). Si un hilo entra en p\u00e1nico, se propaga.\n\n## Beneficios\n*   **Compartir sin Sobrecarga**: Puedes prestar referencias (`&mut T`) sin `Arc` si pruebas acceso disjunto.\n*   **Paralelismo Fork-Join**: Ideal para dividir arrays en trozos y procesarlos en paralelo sin asignaci\u00f3n de heap."}', false, NULL, NULL, 'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!("Chunk 1 processed");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!("Chunk 2 processed");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!("Results: {:?}", data);\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!("Chunk 1 processed");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!("Chunk 2 processed");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!("Results: {:?}", data);\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!("Chunk 1 processed");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!("Chunk 2 processed");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!("Results: {:?}", data);\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!("Chunk 1 processed");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!("Chunk 2 processed");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!("Results: {:?}", data);\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!("Chunk 1 processed");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!("Chunk 2 processed");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!("Results: {:?}", data);\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!("Chunk 1 processed");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!("Chunk 2 processed");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!("Results: {:?}", data);\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!(\"Chunk 1 processed\");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!(\"Chunk 2 processed\");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!(\"Results: {:?}\", data);\n}', NULL, E'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!("Chunk 1 processed");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!("Chunk 2 processed");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!("Results: {:?}", data);\n}', NULL, E'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (first, second) = data.split_at_mut(3);\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in first { *x *= 2; }\n            println!("Chunk 1 processed");\n        });\n        \n        s.spawn(|| {\n            for x in second { *x += 10; }\n            println!("Chunk 2 processed");\n        });\n    }); // Blocks here until both threads finish\n\n    println!("Results: {:?}", data);\n}', NULL, 'use std::thread;\n\nfn main() {\n    let mut data = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6];\n\n    // Modify data in parallel without Arc/Mutex\n    thread::scope(|s| {\n        let (f