       name: name_lit.value(),\n            count: count_lit.base10_parse()?,\n        })\n    }\n}\n*/', NULL, '/*\nuse syn::{parse::Parse, parse::ParseStream, Result, Token};\n\nstruct MyArgs {\n    name: String,\n    count: u32,\n}\n\nimpl Parse for MyArgs {\n    fn parse(input: ParseStream) -> Result<Self> {\n        // Expect: \"Name\", 10\n        let name_lit: syn::LitStr = input.parse()?;\n        input.parse::<Token![,]>()?; // Comma\n        let count_lit: syn::LitInt = input.parse()?;\n        \n        Ok(MyArgs {\n            name: name_lit.value(),\n            count: count_lit.base10_parse()?,\n        })\n    }\n}\n*/', 1);
INSERT INTO chapters (id, module_id, title, content, is_quiz, quiz_data, "order") VALUES ('75890e16-1329-5bfe-b55f-6a646df03941', 'c261c64d-4603-5b36-bac5-e8428523ec62', '{"EN": "Testing & Debugging", "ES": "Testing y Debugging"}', '{"EN": "# Debugging Macros\n\nMacros are notoriously hard to debug because the compiler error points to the macro invocation, not the generated code.\n\n## Tools\n1.  **cargo-expand**: Runs the macro expansion pass and shows you the resulting Rust code file. Extremely useful to check if `quote!` is doing what you think it is.\n2.  **trybuild**: A testing harness for UI tests. It lets you write tests that check if a macro *fails to compile* with a specific error message. This is crucial for providing good developer experience (DX) for users of your macro.\n\n## Best Practices\n*   Keep the macro logic small. Delegate the heavy logic to a standard function if possible.\n*   Always verify inputs explicitly and emit helpful errors using `syn::Error::new_spanned`.", "ES": "# Debugging de Macros\n\nLas macros son notoriamente dif\u00edciles de depurar porque el error del compilador apunta a la invocaci\u00f3n, no al c\u00f3digo generado.\n\n## Herramientas\n1.  **cargo-expand**: Corre el paso de expansi\u00f3n y te muestra el archivo de c\u00f3digo Rust resultante. Extremadamente \u00fatil para verificar `quote!`.\n2.  **trybuild**: Un arn\u00e9s de pruebas para UI tests. Te permite escribir pruebas que verifiquen si una macro *falla al compilar* con un mensaje de error espec\u00edfico. Crucial para buena experiencia de desarrollador (DX).\n\n## Buenas Pr\u00e1cticas\n*   Mant\u00e9n la l\u00f3gica de la macro peque\u00f1a. Delega la l\u00f3gica pesada a funciones est\u00e1ndar si es posible.\n*   Verifica entradas expl\u00edcitamente y emite errores \u00fatiles con `syn::Error::new_spanned`."}', false, NULL, NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass(\"tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs\");\n    t.compile_fail(\"tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs\");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!(\"Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!\");\n}', NULL, E'// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, E'// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, E'// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass(\"tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs\");\n    t.compile_fail(\"tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs\");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!(\"Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!\");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass(\"tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs\");\n    t.compile_fail(\"tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs\");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!(\"Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!\");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass("tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs");\n    t.compile_fail("tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!");\n}', NULL, '// Example trybuild usage in tests/ui.rs\n\n/*\n#[test]\nfn ui() {\n    let t = trybuild::TestCases::new();\n    t.pass(\"tests/ui/01-successful-invocation.rs\");\n    t.compile_fail(\"tests/ui/02-invalid-syntax.rs\");\n}\n*/\n\nfn main() {\n    println!(\"Testing compile errors is just as important as testing success!\");\n}', 2);
INSERT INTO courses (id, slug, title, description, level, image_url) VALUES ('3b0900dd-7a79-5b0b-a7f8-8348bad75808', 'rust-tower', '{"EN": "Tower: Modular Services", "ES": "Tower: Servicios Modulares"}', '{"EN": "Deep dive into the Tower ecosystem. Learn the Service trait, Layers, and how to build reusable middleware for Axum, Hyper, and Tonic.", "ES": "Profundiza en el ecosistema Tower. Aprende el trait Service, Layers y c\u00f3mo construir middleware reutilizable para Axum, Hyper y Tonic."}', 'Advanced', 'https://placehold.co/800x500/d97706/FFFFFF/png?text=Tower+Ecosystem&font=roboto');
INSERT INTO modules (id, course_id, title, "order") VALUES ('64ec9a3a-6b15-57cd-9d1f-d33ccff3af86', '3b0900dd-7a79-5b0b-a7f8-8348bad75808', '{"EN": "1. The Service Trait", "ES": "1. El Trait Service"}', 1);
INSERT INTO chapters (id, module_id, title, content, is_quiz, quiz_data, "order") VALUES ('0c57c3df-8dbf-5066-82de-e8e4b0ee4bd6', '64ec9a3a-6b15-57cd-9d1f-d33ccff3af86', '{"EN": "Request, Response, Future", "ES": "Petici\u00f3n, Respuesta, Futuro"}', '{"EN": "# The Tower Philosophy\n\nTower is a library of modular and reusable components for building robust networking clients and servers. At its core lies the `Service` trait.\n\n## The Abstraction\nA `Service` is simply an asynchronous function from a `Request` to a `Response`.\n```rust\npub trait Service<Request> {\n    type Response;\n    type Error;\n    type Future: Future<Output = Result<Self::Response, Self::Error>>;\n\n    fn poll_ready(&mut self, cx: &mut Context<''_>) -> Poll<Result<(), Self::Error>>;\n    fn call(&mut self, req: Request) -> Self::Future;\n}\n```\n\n## Backpressure (`poll_ready`)\nBefore calling a service, you **must** call `poll_ready`. This allows the service to say \"I am too busy, please wait\" (returning `Poll::Pending`) or \"I am ready\" (returning `Poll::Ready(Ok(()))`). This is how Tower handles backpressure and load shedding natively.", "ES": "# La Filosof\u00eda de Tower\n\nTower es una librer\u00eda de componentes modulares y reutilizables para construir clientes y servidores de red robustos. En su n\u00facleo yace el trait `Service`.\n\n## La Abstracci\u00f3n\nUn `Service` es simplemente una funci\u00f3n as\u00edncrona de una `Request` (Petici\u00f3n) a una `Response` (Respuesta).\n\n## Backpressure (`poll_ready`)\nAntes de llamar a un servicio, **debes** llamar a `poll_ready`. Esto permite al servicio decir \"Estoy muy ocupado, espera\" (retornando `Poll::Pending`) o \"Estoy listo\" (retornando `Poll::Ready(Ok(()))`). As\u00ed es como Tower maneja la contrapresi\u00f3n (backpressure) y el rechazo de carga (load shedding) nativamente."}', false, NULL, NULL, 'use std::future::Future;\nuse std::pin::Pin;\nuse std::task::{Context, Poll};\n\n// A simple service that adds 1 to a number\nstruct AddOneService;\n\n// Mocking the Service trait implementation structure\n// In real code, you implement tower::Service\nimpl AddOneService {\n    fn poll_ready(&mut self, _cx: &mut Context<''_>) -> Poll<Result<(), ()>> {\n        // Always ready to accept requests\n        Poll::Ready(Ok(()))\n    }\n\n    fn call(&mut self, req: i32) -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<i32, ()>>>> {\n        // Return a future that resolves to req + 1\n        Box::pin(async move {\n            Ok(req + 1)\n        })\n    }\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Tower abstracts ''Request -> Response'' logic.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::future::Future;\nuse std::pin::Pin;\nuse std::task::{Context, Poll};\n\n// A simple service that adds 1 to a number\nstruct AddOneService;\n\n// Mocking the Service trait implementation structure\n// In real code, you implement tower::Service\nimpl AddOneService {\n    fn poll_ready(&mut self, _cx: &mut Context<''_>) -> Poll<Result<(), ()>> {\n        // Always ready to accept requests\n        Poll::Ready(Ok(()))\n    }\n\n    fn call(&mut self, req: i32) -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<i32, ()>>>> {\n        // Return a future that resolves to req + 1\n        Box::pin(async move {\n            Ok(req + 1)\n        })\n    }\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Tower abstracts ''Request -> Response'' logic.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::future::Future;\nuse std::pin::Pin;\nuse std::task::{Context, Poll};\n\n// A simple service that adds 1 to a number\nstruct AddOneService;\n\n// Mocking the Service trait implementation structure\n// In real code, you implement tower::Service\nimpl AddOneService {\n    fn poll_ready(&mut self, _cx: &mut Context<''_>) -> Poll<Result<(), ()>> {\n        // Always ready to accept requests\n        Poll::Ready(Ok(()))\n    }\n\n    fn call(&mut self, req: i32) -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<i32, ()>>>> {\n        // Return a future that resolves to req + 1\n        Box::pin(async move {\n            Ok(req + 1)\n        })\n    }\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Tower abstracts ''Request -> Response'' logic.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::future::Future;\nuse std::pin::Pin;\nuse std::task::{Context, Poll};\n\n// A simple service that adds 1 to a number\nstruct AddOneService;\n\n// Mocking the Service trait implementation structure\n// In real code, you implement tower::Service\nimpl AddOneService {\n    fn poll_ready(&mut self, _cx: &mut Context<''_>) -> Poll<Result<(), ()>> {\n        // Always ready to accept requests\n        Poll::Ready(Ok(()))\n    }\n\n    fn call(&mut self, req: i32) -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<i32, ()>>>> {\n        // Return a future that resolves to req + 1\n        Box::pin(async move {\n            Ok(req + 1)\n        })\n    }\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Tower abstracts ''Request -> Response'' logic.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::future::Future;\nuse std::pin::Pin;\nuse std::task::{Context, Poll};\n\n// A simple service that adds 1 to a number\nstruct AddOneService;\n\n// Mocking the Service trait implementation structure\n// In real code, you implement tower::Service\nimpl AddOneService {\n    fn poll_ready(&mut self, _cx: &mut Context<''_>) -> Poll<Result<(), ()>> {\n        // Always ready to accept requests\n        Poll::Ready(Ok(()))\n    }\n\n    fn call(&mut self, req: i32) -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = Result<i32, ()>>>> {\n        // Return a future that resolves to req + 1\n        Box::pin(async move {\n            Ok(req + 1)\n        })\n    }\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    println!("Tower abstracts ''Request -> Response'' logic.");\n}', NULL, 'use std::future::Future;\nuse std::pin::Pin;\nuse std::task::{Context, Poll};\n\n// A simple service that adds 1 to a number\nstruct AddOneService;\n\n// Mocking the Service trait implementation structure\n// In real code, you implement tower::Service\nimpl AddOneService {\n    fn poll_ready(&mut self, _cx: &mut Context<''_>) -> Poll<Result<(), ()>> {\n        // Always ready to accept requests